1.2 The Technology Stack: How We Got Here

The acceleration from 2020 to 2026 was not just about adoption. It was about capability. The technology stack for building agents evolved dramatically over this period.

1.2.1 The Core Model

In 2020, GPT-3 was state of the art. By 2026, the landscape included:

· GPT-4o and o-series (OpenAI): Strong reasoning, tool use, multimodal
· Claude 3.5/3.7 (Anthropic): Safety-focused, strong at long contexts
· Gemini 2 (Google): Deep integration with Google services, strong multimodal
· Llama 3 (Meta): Open, performant, widely adopted
· DeepSeek R1 (DeepSeek): Strong reasoning, open architecture
· Mistral Large (Mistral): European alternative, strong on compliance

Each generation improved not just on raw benchmarks, but on the capabilities that matter for agents: reasoning, tool use, instruction following, and self-correction.

1.2.2 The Orchestration Layer

By 2024, it was clear that raw models were not enough. You needed an orchestration layer to manage memory, tools, and multi-agent coordination.

The major frameworks:

Framework Strengths Primary Use Case
LangChain Mature, large ecosystem General-purpose agent building
LangGraph Stateful, cyclic workflows Complex, multi-step agents
AutoGen Multi-agent orchestration Agent teams, role-playing
CrewAI Role-based agent design Simulating organizational structures
Semantic Kernel Microsoft integration Enterprise Copilot extensions
LlamaIndex Data connectivity RAG-heavy agents

Each framework encoded different assumptions about how agents should work. LangGraph, for example, treated agents as nodes in a graph, enabling complex, cyclical workflows. AutoGen focused on conversation between specialized agents. The diversity reflected a field still finding its standard patterns.

1.2.3 Memory and State

Early agents had no memory beyond their context window. By 2026, memory architectures had matured into layered systems:

· Short-term memory: The context window (now up to 1M+ tokens in some models)
· Long-term memory: Vector databases storing embeddings of past interactions
· Episodic memory: Structured logs of agent actions and outcomes
· Semantic memory: Knowledge bases and world models

The combination enabled agents that could learn from experience, recall past interactions, and maintain coherence across extended engagements.

1.2.4 Tools and APIs

In 2022, tools meant hard-coded functions. By 2026, agents could discover, learn, and use tools dynamically:

· Function calling became standard in major models
· OpenAPI specifications allowed agents to understand API structure
· Browser use (Claude's "computer use," OpenAI's Operator) enabled agents to interact with any web application
· Code execution environments let agents write, run, and debug their own code

The result: agents that could interact with the digital world almost as fluidly as humans.

