1.3 The Evolution of Agent Capabilities

To understand the acceleration, it helps to trace a single capability over time.

2020: Simple Q&A

User: "What's the weather in Paris?"
System: [Retrieves weather data] "It's 18°C and cloudy."

2022: Multi-step with fixed flow

User: "Book a flight to Paris next week."
System: "I need your departure city, preferred dates, and budget."
[Follows predetermined conversation flow]

2024: Goal-oriented with tool use

User: "Find me a cheap flight to Paris next week and book it if it's under $500."
System: [Searches flights] "I found one for $480 on Tuesday. Shall I book it?"
User: "Yes."
System: [Calls booking API] "Booked. Confirmation sent to your email."

2026: Autonomous with planning and memory

User: "I need to be in Paris for a meeting on the 15th. Handle the logistics."
System: [Checks calendar] "You have a conflict on the 14th. Shall I reschedule?"
User: "Handle it."
System: [Reschedules meeting, searches flights, books hotel based on past preferences, adds to calendar, sends itinerary] "All set. Your colleague Jean-Pierre has been notified you'll be in the office."

The difference is not just in capability. It's in agency. The 2026 agent pursues goals across multiple steps, resolves conflicts, makes decisions based on preferences, and coordinates with other systems—all with minimal human direction.

