3.6 Multi-Agent Systems: Teams That Work Together

The most important evolution in agent architecture (2025-2026) is the shift from single agents to agent teams.

3.6.1 Why Teams?

Single agents have fundamental limitations:

· Context constraints: One agent can only hold so much information
· Cognitive load: Complex tasks overwhelm a single reasoning thread
· Self-correction: An agent that makes mistakes has no internal check
· Specialization: Different tasks require different capabilities

Teams overcome these limitations by distributing work across specialized agents.

3.6.2 Common Agent Roles

In multi-agent systems, agents typically assume specialized roles:

Role Responsibility Example
Planner Decomposes goals into tasks, creates execution plan Break "plan a conference" into venue, speakers, catering
Executor Performs specific actions using tools Book venue, send invitations, process registrations
Critic Reviews outputs, identifies errors, suggests improvements Check that venue is available, verify budget
Researcher Gathers information from external sources Find speaker availability, research catering options
Coordinator Manages communication between agents, resolves conflicts Ensure planner and executor stay aligned
Monitor Tracks progress, detects failures, alerts humans Notice if booking fails, notify if budget exceeded

3.6.3 Team Architectures

Different tasks require different team structures:

Hierarchical: A supervisor agent delegates to worker agents, reviewing their outputs and providing feedback. This mirrors traditional management structures and works well for well-defined tasks with clear delegation.

Peer-to-peer: Agents collaborate as equals, each contributing specialized capabilities. This suits creative or exploratory tasks where no single agent has the full picture.

Debate: Agents argue for different positions, with a judge agent (or human) deciding. This surfaces diverse perspectives and can improve decision quality.

Swarm: Many simple agents coordinate through emergent behavior, each following local rules. This scales well but is harder to control.

3.6.4 The ClickUp Model: Agent Hierarchies

The ClickUp deployment described in Chapter 2 represents a new organizational form: agent hierarchies.

Zeb Evans, ClickUp's CEO, describes it: "We now have over 3,258 agents working alongside 1,300 humans. Managers' agents will manage their ICs' agents—overseeing them for human-in-the-loop interactions."

This is not a flat team of agents. It's a multi-level hierarchy where agents manage other agents, with humans only at the top. The implications are profound:

· Scalability: One human can oversee hundreds of agents through intermediate management layers
· Consistency: Management agents enforce policies and standards across worker agents
· Learning: Management agents can aggregate lessons from many workers and propagate improvements

This structure, adapted from human organizational design, may become the dominant pattern for large-scale agent deployment.

