3.7 Evaluation: How We Know If Agents Work

As agents move into production, evaluation becomes critical. How do we know if an agent is doing its job correctly?

3.7.1 Evaluation Dimensions

Agent evaluation spans multiple dimensions:

Task completion: Did the agent achieve the goal? This is the primary metric, but not the only one.

Efficiency: How many steps, how many tokens, how much time did it take? An agent that completes tasks but consumes excessive resources is not production-ready.

Reliability: Does it succeed consistently, or only under ideal conditions?

Safety: Did it take any unsafe actions? Expose sensitive data? Violate policies?

Explainability: Can we understand why it made the decisions it did?

User satisfaction: For human-facing agents, do users report positive experiences?

3.7.2 Evaluation Methods

Benchmarking: Standardized tasks with known correct answers. The AgentBench and WebArena benchmarks provide controlled environments for comparing agents.

Human evaluation: Trained evaluators review agent outputs and interactions, scoring on multiple dimensions. Expensive but gold-standard.

Automated metrics: For tasks with clear success criteria (code generation, data retrieval), automated tests can verify correctness.

A/B testing: In production, compare agent variants on real user interactions, measuring task completion and satisfaction.

Red teaming: Deliberately attempt to make agents fail—through adversarial inputs, edge cases, or complex scenarios—to identify weaknesses.

3.7.3 The Production Gap

Benchmark performance does not guarantee production performance. Agents that excel in controlled environments often fail in the wild due to:

· Unexpected user inputs
· Real-world data messiness
· Integration failures
· Latency and reliability constraints
· Cost overruns

The gap between benchmark success and production reliability is one of the most significant challenges in agent deployment. Closing it requires rigorous testing, gradual rollouts, and robust monitoring.

---

3.8 The State of the Art: What Agents Can and Cannot Do (March 2026)

After six years of acceleration, it's worth taking stock of current capabilities.

3.8.1 What Works Well

Structured knowledge work: Research, analysis, summarization, report generation—agents excel at tasks that involve finding, organizing, and synthesizing information.

Code generation and debugging: Agents can write substantial amounts of working code, identify bugs, and suggest fixes. In many organizations, they are standard tools for developers.

Customer service automation: For routine inquiries, agents handle 70-80% of tickets without human intervention. Complex or sensitive cases still escalate.

Workflow automation: In structured domains with clear rules and APIs, agents can execute multi-step processes reliably.

Data analysis: Agents can query databases, generate visualizations, and produce insights from structured data.

3.8.2 What's Emerging

Multimodal understanding: Agents that see, hear, and interact with the physical world are moving from labs to early deployment. Computer use capabilities allow agents to operate any software a human can.

Long-term planning: Agents can now maintain coherence across hundreds or thousands of steps, remembering earlier decisions and adjusting plans as conditions change.

Learning from experience: With episodic memory and reflection, agents improve over time, learning from successes and failures.

Multi-agent coordination: Teams of agents working together on complex tasks are moving from research to production.

3.8.3 What Remains Hard

Common sense: Agents still make obvious mistakes that no human would make—confusing dates, misunderstanding simple instructions, acting on false premises.

Novel situations: When faced with genuinely new scenarios, agents struggle. They rely on patterns in training data; true novelty breaks those patterns.

High-stakes decisions: In situations with significant consequences—medical diagnosis, financial trading, legal judgment—human oversight remains essential.

Physical interaction: While improving rapidly, agents in the physical world (robots, drones, manufacturing) remain far behind digital agents in capability and reliability.

Self-awareness: Agents don't know what they don't know. They confidently assert falsehoods, pursue impossible goals, and fail to recognize their own limitations.

