3.9 The Technical Stack: Summary

A modern agent is not a monolith. It is a layered system:

Layer Components Function
Core Model LLM, multimodal model Reasoning, planning, generation
Memory Context window, vector DB, structured logs Remembering across time
Tools APIs, code executors, browser controllers Acting on the world
Orchestration Frameworks (LangGraph, AutoGen, etc.) Tying it all together
Multi-Agent Specialized roles, team structures Scaling capability
Evaluation Benchmarks, human review, monitoring Ensuring quality

Each layer is itself complex, with multiple options and design decisions. The art of building agents is choosing and combining these layers appropriately for the task at hand.

---

Key Takeaways

1. Agents are systems, not models. A foundation model provides reasoning, but memory, tools, and orchestration are equally essential.
2. Memory is layered: short-term (context), long-term (vectors), episodic (logs), and semantic (knowledge). Effective agents use all four.
3. Tools enable action. The tool ecosystem has expanded dramatically, from APIs to code execution to browser control.
4. Orchestration frameworks encode different assumptions. Choose the framework that matches your task: LangGraph for complex workflows, AutoGen for multi-agent teams, LlamaIndex for RAG-heavy applications.
5. The ReAct pattern (Reason + Act) is foundational, but advanced patterns (Tree of Thoughts, Reflexion) extend it for complex tasks.
6. Multi-agent systems are the new frontier. Teams of specialized agents outperform single agents on complex tasks. Hierarchical agent organizations (agents managing agents) are emerging in production.
7. Evaluation is multidimensional: task completion, efficiency, reliability, safety, explainability, and user satisfaction all matter. Benchmark performance does not guarantee production success.
8. The state of the art is impressive but bounded. Agents excel at structured knowledge work, code generation, and customer service. They struggle with common sense, novelty, high-stakes decisions, and physical interaction.

